Lesson Plan: Basic CSS Styling for HTML Elements

In this lesson, we will be learning about basic CSS styling for HTML elements. Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) is a web design language used to style HTML documents. With CSS, you can change the look and feel of your website, adding colors, fonts, and layout designs.

To apply CSS to an HTML document, you must first establish a link between them, usually by adding a link element in the head section of your HTML file. Once you’ve linked the files, you can begin styling the HTML elements.

An example of a CSS style is changing the background color of an HTML body. By using the following CSS code, we can set the background color to red:

body {
  background-color: red;
}

To apply these styles to HTML elements, you can use different selectors, such as ID selectors, class selectors, and element selectors, among others.

Practice problem: Create a new HTML document and apply CSS styles to change the font size and color of your headings to match your preferred style.

Solution: To change the font size and color of your headings, you can use CSS code like this:

h1 {
  font-size: 36px;
  color: blue;
}

h2 {
  font-size: 24px;
  color: green;
}

Summary: In this lesson, we learned about basic CSS styling for HTML elements. We explored how to apply CSS to an HTML document, how to add selectors, and how to modify the appearance of HTML elements using CSS.
